{"/service/ndnp/oru/batch_oru_longspur_ver01/data/sn88086023/0020219462A/1908010401/0711.xml":{"full_text":"EIGHT PAGES.\nDAILY EAST OREGONIAN, PENDLETON, OREGON. SATURDAY, JANUARY 4, 1B08.\nPAGE SEVEN.\nFresh\nCandies, Nuts, Cakes\nand Fastry.\nFresh Oysters in bulk dellv\nered to any part of the city.\nFINE LUNCHES SERVED.\nj HOHDACH'S j\nBAKERY\nAND\nOYSTER\nHOUSE.\nUUUBE.\n221 V.. rvnrt fit 'Ptinno main an\nPaint Your Home\nWITH 17 PAINT\nA little painting here and\nthere will help It looks wonder\nfully. Some nice, bright, new\nwall paper lend a freshness to\nany room. Our stock of wall\npaper never was more com\nplete patterns In endless vari\nety and every one new and up-to-date\nIn color design. Better\ncome In and let us show them\nto you and tell you what it will\ncoat for your whole house or\none room.\nPendleton Paint Store\nE J, Murphy.\n1 2 1 E. Court Black 381\nINSURANCE\nLivermore fi Bickers\nRoom 12, Judd Bldg.\nPendleton Oregon\nLarge Quantity of the Famous\nRock Spring\nNow on Hand\nThe coal that produces heat\nand not dirt. Also fine lot of\ngood clry wood.\nDutch Henry\nOf floe, Pendleton Ice A Cold Storage\nCompany. Thone Main 178.\nColumbia Bar\nand\nRooming House\nr'\"'\nF. X. Schempp Estate\nFine Wines, Liquors,\nand Cigars.\nNewly furnished and np-to-date.\nRooming House In Connection.\n32ft JUAIN STREET.\nWE DO NOT APE\nOTHER BRANDS,\nof Wines and Liquors, but we rather\nfanoy that ours are much Imitated on\naccount of their supreme popularity.\n\"Good wine or liquor needs no bush,\"\nand the first taste of our brands al\nways makes friends for the future.\nThere is a purity, an enticing and\npleasing flavor about them that al\nways satisfies the real Judge of good\nLiquor. Doctors are recommending\nour brands now on account of their\nproved purity.\nJOHN GAGEN,\nCourt street. 'Phone Main 150\nDally Bast Oregonlan by carrier,\nonly II cents a week.\nlots Mr\nV\nAMONG THE EXCHANGES\nOF THE\nINLAND EMPIRE\nMachinery for Ills 31 Inc.\nFrank Turner, a minor who has\nJust returned from the up-river die\ntrlct, brings the report that the work\nof transferring the machinery for the\nquartz mill from North Powder to the\nMulr mines will bo commenced this\nweek, says the La Grande Star.\nThe conditions are now the best\nthat could be desired for this class of\nwork. There is plenty of snow all\nalong the route, and by the use of\nheavy sleds the mill machinery can\nbe transferred with but little effort,\nMr. Turner says there Is an unusual\namount of snow in the high hills. At\nthe Eureka claim, where he has qust\nfinished some development work, the\nsnow is live leet deep, on tne sum\nmit, between North Powder and Car\nson, there Is seven feet of snow, and\nIn Cable Cove, 10 feet.\nAll the plans for the 20-stamp mill\nbuilding are completed and the mill\nsite Is In readiness for the work of\nconstruction. At the sawmill a nun\ndred, thousand feet of logs have been\ndelivered for timbers for the mill and\nmines.\nMr. Turner figures that \"there\ncannot help\" but be a lively camp up\nthe river this year.\nInland Empire Makes Gain.\nFifty-one million dollars is the es\ntimated value of the crops produced\non farms In the inland empire during\nthe season of 1907, and of this\namount the farmers received $37,\n000,000 for their wheat, $4,000,000\nfor barley, 2,600,000 for oats and\n$7,600,000 for potatoes, hops, grasses\nand grains not mentioned In the fore\ngoing, says a Spokane paper.\nThis shows a gain of 25 per cent\nover 1906, and. Judging from the\npreparations that have already been\nmade, there will be a similar If not\ngreater Increase In 1908. The basis\nfor this Is that the farmers In the\ndistrict bought $1,600,000 worth of\nmachinery and Implements' last year,\nor a (fain of SO per cent ovr 1906,\nwhich, until 1907, was the banner year\nIn the history of the country.\nMore than 80 per cent of the wheat\ncrop was produced In eastern Wash\nington.\nChicken IiiiKinc) Good.\n\"Eggs are 11 cents a dozen In\nMichigan, where 1 came from,\" said\nF. Morton, this morning. \"I find\nthey are 45 cents here, which makes\na difference In the cost of a meal at\nHIS FORECAST\nNew York, Jank 4. Congress will\nreassemble Monday and the senators\nand representatives, refreshed by a\nperiod of holiday cheer, will enter j\nupon the real work of the session\nwith renewed vim. It Is likely that\nthe reopening of congress will be'ln the United States district court at\ntaken advantage oi vy ine irmnua\nand supporters of Speaker Joseph\nCannon to formally announce his\ncandidacy for the republican presl-.\ndentlal nomination. Scores of con-\ngressmen\nfavor Cannon' and the j\nlaunching of the boom will be at\ntended by considerable enthusiasm.\nPractically all of the republican mem\nbers of the house who have no fa\nvorite sons in their own states are\nsolidly back of the speaker.\nInharmonious conditions In the\nnavy department, which led to the\nresignation of Rear Admiral Wlllardl\nH. Brownson from the office of chief\nof the naval bureau of navigation,\nill l'kely receive the attention of\nboth houses during the coming week.\nThe resignation of Brownson. follow\ning close 6n the heels of Henry Reut\nerdahl's attack on the bureau sys\ntem of the navy department, has re\nvealed the strife\" existing In the con\nduct of the navy and the need for a\nmore harmonious administration. As\nresult, congress will undoubtedly\ngive a thorough airing to the causes\nhlch have operated to bring about\nconditions that all the officers of the\nnavy are themselves anxious to have\nremedied.\nThe demand for the relief of the\nfinancial situation has become wlde-\npread and when the -congressmen\nmet Monday they will be presented\nwith numerous petitions from com\nmercial bodies all over the country,\nasking for a speedy consideration of\nthe subject.\nTliaw Trial Again.\nThe trial of Harry Kendall Thaw\nfor the murder of Stanford White Is\nset for Monday, before Justice Victor\nDowllng In the criminal branch\nof the supreme court In New York\ncity.' It Is expected that there will\nbe little delay and that the work of\nsecuring a Jury will, be commenced\nalmost Immediately and be continued\nwith day and, night sessions, until\ncompleted. District Attorney Jerome\nwill again conduct the prosecution,\nand Thaw will be defended by Mar\ntin W. Littleton, assisted by several\nother prominent attorneys. Insanity\nill be the plea of the defendant, ac\ncording to the present plans -of the\nfenso. Any attempt to send Thaw\nto a madhouse will be fought by his\nattorney who declare that his In\nanity was only temporary and In\nduced by the recital of the wrongs\nsuffered by his wife, Evelyn Nesblt\nThaw, at the hands of Stanford\nWhite.. Mrs. Thaw will again be the\nprincipal witness for the defense.\nStandard Oil Camvt\nThe hearing before Judge Franklin\nFerrlss In the government's suit to\ndissolve the Standard Oil company of\nNew Jersey, the $100,000,000 parent\nconcern of the \"oil trust,\" will be re-\numed In New York Monday. A\na short order house. I have made\nmoney on eggs at the Michigan price,\nOne certainly could make a handsome\nprofit at three times that much. If\npeople here ate eggs like they do\nelsewhere the price would be higher\nthan that I figure that the hennery\nIs overlooked In this country. I think\nof trying to profit by other people's\nmisfortunes. I have come to Yaki\nma to stay.\" Yakima Republic.\nAfter the Ilorscbeatcrs.\nSheriff Shutt, who Is making war\non horsebeaters In this county, learn\ned last Monday that John Carter, a\nMonument freighter, who Is hauling\nwheat for the Eight Mile farmers, had\ntaken a fence post, nearly beating one\nof his horses to death, punching the\nhorse's eyes out In his rage. The\nsheriff Immediately Instructed his\ndeputy at lone, W. C. Cason, to arrest\nCarter and take him before Justice\nPerkins, which was done and Carter\nwas fined '50 and costs, amounting\nto $80 In all. Heppner Times.\nHeppner Postmaster Reappointed.\nPostmaster W. W. Smead received\na few days ago his appointment as\npostmaster of Heppner for four years\nhis term having expired in November\nlast.\nMr. Smead's administration of the\naffairs of the office has doubtless\ngiven general satisfaction during his\nterm just past as he had no opposi\ntion whatever for reappointment. Al\nso his management of the office has\ncertainly been sufficiently satisfactory\nto the department to merit his reap\npointment. Heppner Times.\nNarrow Eape from Drowning.\nFred Gerllnger, who Is chopping\nwood for J. W. Walker, came near\ndrowning In the Walla Walla river\none day this week, says the Wallula\nGateway. He attempted to cross the\nstream In an old boat, when the craft\nbecame unmanageable and he was\ndrifting toward the rapids at the\nmouth of the river. He grabbed some\nwillows when the boat shot from\nunder him and he was plunged Into\nthe Ice cold water. He managed to\nreach the shore, but came near per\nishing before reaching camp.\nDisturbed the Congregation.\nThe person who disturbed the con\ngregation last Sunday by continually\ncoughing Is requested to buy a bot\ntle of Foley's Honey and Tar. Pen\ndleton Drug Co.\nFOB COMING WEEK\nmass of testimony which has' been\ngiven In other states against the\nStandard will be Introduced. What\nis known as the \"Little Alton\" case\nagainst the Standard Oil company of\nIndiana Is also set for trial Monday\nviui:au. iij uua vase wic ouiiiuaru\nIs charged with the acceptance of\nrebates from the Chicago Alton\nrailway from Whiting, Ind., to St\nLouis. The Indictment contains 134\ncounts and if the company Is found\nguilty In all of them It will be sub\nject to a fine of $2,680,000.\nElldns' Law Tost.\nAttorney General Bonaparte will\nprobably make his appearance in the\nUnited States supreme court as the\ngovernment's chief law officer Mon\nday, when the rebate case against the\nGreat Northern, In which the rail\nroad company Is under sentence to\npay a fine of $16,000, is to be argued.\nThis Is the case In 'which the com\npany seeks to test the Elklns law, un\nder which the fine was Imposed, the\nattorneys for the. def(ndants urging\nthat the law was repealed by the\nrailroad rate law passed by congress.\nThe supreme court has also ae. for\nargument next week the case Involv\ning' whether the land owned by the\nUniversity of the South at Sewanee,\nTenn., Is subject to taxation under\nthe laws of that state.\nTwo Cent Fare Law.\nAnother case Involving the power\nof the federal courts to interfere in\nthe execution of state railroad rate\nlaws will be taken up by the United\nStates supreme court on Monday,\nwhen the federal Judges for, the dis\ntrict of Nebraska are ordered to ap\npear and show cause why a writ of\nmandamus, asked for by the state of\nficials of Nebraska to prevent Inter\nference With the Inforcement of the\ntwo cent fare law. should not issue.\nReturn of Prosperity.\nIt Is estimated that not less than\n100,000 men, who have been Idle for\nseveral weeks owing to the shutdown\nof plants In the great industrial cen\nters of the country, will return to\nwork. In the steel mills and factor\nies in the Pittsburg district alone about\n40.000 men will share In the return\ning prosperity. In Cleveland at least\n10,000 men will resume work at their\nformer occupations, and hundreds of\ngreat factories and mills In other cit\nies will begin operations on Monday.\nWHERE MEN AND WOMEN SUF\nFER. Roth men and women suffer from\noverwork and overwbrry. i:id so both\nmay be cured by using the same rem\nedy. The best remedy for such con\nditions is Sexlne Pills; no matter\nhow badly run down or how nervous\nand Irritable a person may be, Sex\nlne Pills are guaranteed to restore\nstrength, health and energy. Price\n$1 a box, six boxes for 15, fully\nguaranteed on the money-back plan.\nAddress or call the Pendleton Drug\ncompany. This Is the store that sells\nall the principal remedies and does\nnot substitute.\nr mm im mmim i 